  "text": "coding sequences in Pf-A and Pf-B strains, the authors reasoned that regulatory mutations were more likely to underlie their different chemical profiles and examined the GacA-GacS two-component system responsible for regulating virulence factors in related Gram-negative bacteria [CITATION_1] . Indeed, a point mutation in the global activator A (gacA) gene of the Pf-B strain inserts a stop codon directly upstream of a sequence encoding a helix-turn-helix motif, resulting in a truncated gene product that cannot bind DNA and activate GacS, the cognate response factor. Like Pf-B, artificial GacA KO mutants of P. fluorescens produce enantiopyochelin, lack chromene and pyrrolnitrin, and can be eaten by amoebae. Finally, a phylogenetic analysis of gacA sequences, including all known strains of P. fluorescens, showed that the Pf-B strain has the only nonfunctional gacA sequence, suggesting that the mutation is a derived condition.",
